indicators.justification:
A lobbying register was created by law in 2016-2017 (law passed in 2016, implemented in 2017). The law (1) and decree (2) contain a definition of lobbying activities and a list of public officials. Lobbying at local level is not yet covered (the reform is drafted but has been delayed several times). 

The High Authority for Transparency in Public Life (HATVP) is in charge of collecting, controlling and publishing the data. The HATVP publishes binding guidelines that complement the law and goes into more details (3). In addition to this main register, there is a sector-specific framework applicable to the tobacco industry that remains active (4).

This lobbying register is covered by the "open data by default" principle, and data must be published as open data as explicitly recalled in the law (5).

The data are published as they are declared by lobbyists, without any verification process prior to publication. The HATVP can proceed to post-publication controls, although this is done with only limited means and legal obstacles. The details of the verification actions undertaken by the HATVP are detailed in its annual reports (5).

Data are not declared activity by activity, and the exact public decision targeted does not have to be declared. Therefore, the datasets are very well structured, but it is impossible to extract automatically all lobbying activities related to one given public decision. In addition, data are aggregated (one "lobbying activity" can agglomerate several "lobbying actions"), which makes it difficult to compare data. Consequently, this lobbying register is a poor tool to trace legislative footprint and it is therefore heavily criticized by civil society (6) and international organisations such as the Council of Europe (7).

(1) Law n°2013-907 on transparency of public life as modified by law n°2016-1691 of Dec 9 2016. Articles 18-1, 18-2 and 18-3. 
""The following people are lobbyists, within the meaning of this section : legal persons (...) of which a director, employee or member has as his or her main or regular activity to influence public decisions, in particular the content of a law or regulatory act, by entering into communication with" (followed by a list of public officials)" https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/loda/id/JORFTEXT000028056315/ 

(2) Decree n°2017-867 of May 9 2017, Annex n°2. https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/loda/article_lc/LEGIARTI000034792690
"Lobbying actions may include
- Organising informal discussions or face-to-face meetings;
- Arranging for a third party to meet with a public office holder;
- Inviting or organising events, meetings or promotional activities;
- Establishing regular correspondence (by email, post, etc.);
- Sending petitions, open letters, leaflets;
- Organising public debates, marches, internet lobbying;
- Organising hearings, formal consultations on legislation or other open consultations;
- Transmitting suggestions to influence the drafting of a public decision;
- Transmitting information and expertise to public decision-makers with a view to convincing them;
- Other: to be specified."

(2) HATVP. "Lignes directrices". October 2018. https://www.hatvp.fr/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Lignes-directrices-octobre-2018.pdf

(4) Code of Public Health, Article L3512 https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000032548837/

(4) Law n°2013-907 on transparency of public life. Article 18-1. "This publication is made in an open format that is freely usable and machine-readable" https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/loda/article_lc/LEGIARTI000033562994

(5) HATVP. "Rapport d'activité 2020". 2021. Part 4, section 3.  https://www.hatvp.fr/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/HATVP_RA20_EN.pdf

(6) Foucraut, Elsa. 2019. "Pour un meilleur encadrement du lobbying". Transparency International France. Chapter 2 https://transparency-france.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/20190926_Rapport_Transparency_International_France-Pour_un_meilleur_encadrement_du_lobbying.pdf

(7) Council of Europe, GRECO. Fifth evaluation round evaluation report France. December 2019. Extract of the executive summary: "Regarding contacts between PTEFs and lobbyists, there is a striking need for more transparency, in particular through asking PTEFs to report publicly and regularly their meetings with lobbyists and the subject-matters discussed. Moreover, the existing register for lobbyists should cover all lobbyists having been in contact with PTEFs – at present, only those who have actively sought to contact PHFEs are required to register, therefore giving only a partial view of the situation."
